\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Would you like to say your name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 My name? Donald Campbell. I went to 
- from Castlebay at sixteen years of age - to - to Leith. But before we got to - get to Leith - by sixteen years of age and the schoolmaster that was there at the time, Mr Smith - I was after leaving school then you see, he called me one afternoon and he 
a
sked me if I would take such and such a job, as a national steward in one of the fishery cruisers, called the Brenda, that was the name. So I took the job. And I was to go away at - such and such a date, from Castlebay and at that time you get to Castleba
y
 - every day from Oban, leaving Oban at six o'clock in the morning. Monday morning coming straight to Tobermory and from Tobermory to Castlebay and Lochboisdale and way up - we used to way as far as Lockmaddy and then - across to Dunvegan and back to Oban
.
 Now - we'll leaving Castlebay at three o'clock in the morning, going straight over, see. And I went away anyway, I went to - a rousing crowd going off, all my own colleagues at school seeing me off. They weren't feeble. And - I arrived in - no, first of 
a
ll - when I went aboard the - the - the steamer, that was - the - the Cygnet, that was her name, the Cygnet, and there was no steerage in that - boat at all only a cabin. And you had to pay extra fare for that. So - I decided to stop - right in the bow of
 
her, in - among coils of ropes. Right through the voyage. Right on to Oban. I got to Oban anyway and I stepped on the railway pier in Oban and - I noticed a policeman further ahead of me. And I say to myself, I know that man. And I went straight to him an
d asked him if he was so and so. Yes, he said, I am. He was a - a - a policeman that joined the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16477639\charrsid5125818 policeforce}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818  - the Argyll policeforce - and from - Borve, you know, the west side of Barra, from Borve. Archie McMillan was his name. So - he says, are you hungry
? Says I, I'll take a cup of tea if I could get it. So he took me for - a restaurant and he gave me a cup of tea, a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16477639\charrsid5125818 sandwich}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818  and he's seen me on the train - to Edinburgh - the Waverley station, and that was one of the biggest stations in the United Kingdom
 at that time, the Waverley in Edinburgh, you may know that yourself. Yes. Well - I got to the Waverley station, and me peeping out then - then - then I would see any signs of Waverley station, the name Waverley station, no, I couldn't see this place. But
 
at last we got there. And now the puzzle to get to Leith because the fishery cruiser was lying in Granton harbour. At the time. And - I got to - I - was on the station and I couldn't see any - there was nothing there but cabs. And I seen a cabby here and 
I
 says to him, could you drive me down to Leith? And I had the address that - for the - licensed grocer man, he was to - to have sent somebody up to meet me, but there was nobody there. So I seen the sign when the cabby says, yes, he says, I'll drive you d
o
wn. So we was peeping out - see if I could see, William McInness, licensed grocer. Shore, Leith, you know. At least - at last we came to them. And I stepped out and I said to the cabby, now he says - now I says, what's the fare? Well he says, it'll be hal
f
 a crown. And I had one half crown in my pocket. One half crown. There you are. And - here you are. I save that's the last. What, he says. Is that the last? Yes, I said, that's the last. All right dear boy, he says, you take that half crown. Whether I may
 see you some other time - when you've got more than that. So - he left. I goes in there and the - a big fellow at the back of the counter, Mr McInness, stares at me and - heavens, he says, I forgot all about sending anybody up to meet you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 How did you get that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
That's from - schoolmaster over there. Seemingly the commander of the - of the Brenda, she used to visit this place you see every - fishery protection - at the time. Which was in full swing at that time in - in Castlebay. And - it was
 through the commander - going and - and asking - if - Mr Smith had any suitable clients for to - for a job. So - he pointed - picked me - for the job. So I went. And - however from - and - where were we - at - at Leith? Aye. That's right, got to the shop
.
 Now - he had a chargehand there belonging to - Fort William. I can't remember his name at the present time, but he belonged to Fort William anyway. He was related to Mr - Mr McInness himself someway or another. And Mr McInness' wife was a Barra woman, se
e
. You see, the - the old Craigar over there. Well she was born and brought up up there, Mrs McInness. And - he sent his chargehand with me down to where this - this chargehand was lodging. And I was to stop there 'til such time as I was to join the - the 
B
renda and - I was there for a fortnight, in and out, on Ferry Road in Leith. And - when the Brenda came in anyway - I was going down to Granton harbour every day but she wasn't there, she wasn't coming in, but she came in at last. And she used to - to moo
r
 and - to moor stern on to the - to the breakwater. That's a long breakwater down there about a mile long. And she was stern on. So I went down, with my bed and baggage and everything. That wasn't much at the time I can assure you. And sent a boat to the 
s
ide of the slip and I went abroad. And I was made very welcome - by the commander, chief officer and the chief steward. They met me and - took charge of me. Showed me my berth where I was to stop. And - I got through all right. We went to sea - and - oh -
 
I was all right 'til - 'til we were - we got to Aberdeen - on the way to Shetland, we were supposed to go up to Shetland on fishery duty. And - oh it was a terrible - it was in the wintertime. It was a terrible - ordeal for me. When we left Aberdeen, you 
k
now - were you ever in Aberdeen? Well you - well there's a terrible bar there going out in - when you're entering the - the harbour, it's a terrible bar, and it was easterly wind, a gale, and we left at four o'clock in the morning. Of course I wasn't up a
t
 that time. I wasn't getting up 'til half past five or six o'clock. And - by the time we - she - got outside, oh boy, she was heel and toe motion there - terrible. Standing up on end. And I got sick. I had to lie down to it. Which never bothered me before
 and I was at sea around these islands umpteen times, but a different motion altogether, you know, to the fishing boats. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 You were in the fishing boats before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
Oh previous, yes. Oh yes. I should have given you that first. But it'll come on -
 it'll come on later. It'll do just the same doesn't it? Yes. Yes. Aye. So - we went out - in the afternoon I was - pretty fair on my feet then. I got on work. When we got to Shetland anyway, to Baltasound first. And we came from Baltasound to Lerwick. We
l
l there was orders there for the commander - what - a fleet of trawlers were poaching in St Magnus Bay. You know St - St Magnus Bay, that's St Magnus Bay on the west side before you get to Papa Stour. Yes. So - we had to put to sea right away, out of Lerw
i
ck and away up, and we got up there about dusk - dark and - the Brenda had two boards - four boards in fact, they put one on each bow - outside - and one on each quarter. F.B.9. Fishers Board 9, see. And she had a mizzen the same as the trawlers, see. And
 it was her bow. And the poor souls, they never - never tumbled - she was among the whole lot before they - any of them knew what - what she was, see. There was twenty-four of them - that he charged that day, for illegal }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2427406\charrsid5125818 perverting}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 . And took the whole dashed lot into L}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16477639\charrsid5125818 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
rwick harbour. And me in my uniform - I was the last aboard, he had to put a man aboard every one of them, see. And - I - I had to get on my uniform and a cap and - the shoulder badge in - in - in the front of it, because there was no badge in
 my cap, see, my uniform cap. And - I was aboard, up in the bridge along with the captain of the trawler, got into Lerwick anyway.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 What was your job on the boat then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5978047\charrsid5125818 Mess}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 room steward. A boy. Well sixteen and a half when I left - Catlebay, that was my - my job, a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2427406\charrsid5125818 
mess room}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
 steward, looking after the officers, see. So I had nothing to do with the commander. And - when - when we went to Lerwick anyway. I got aboard back to my own ship, and there was - once they took their gear ashore, their trawl 
- what they were - the - the gear that they were using for fishing, all that gear was - confiscated and taken ashore. And they were allowed to go away now 'til such time as the court was coming off. See, they were charged and - their court was to be settl
e
d in three weeks or - less than that perhaps. And - court came off anyway. And each one of them was - fined a hundred and fifty pounds. And they were all Aberdeen trawlers, one Hull trawler among them, they were all Aberdeen trawlers and - they - their ge
a
r was taken up to the coastguard and cared for by the coastguards and afterwards sold. See, they would get a chance of buying it - buying their own gear again if they wanted to, see, but they none of them came for their own gear. None of them. It was sold
 to other - firms. And - after that - the day that the - the coast was over. When - when they were going off. Used to - used - you should hear the curses - and the language that was among these }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2427406\charrsid5125818 trawler men}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 . Good heavens. I'm not going to mention that. And - and - bue a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16477639\charrsid5125818 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
r - oh - cursing the commander oh right and left, I don't know how the devil he - did he manage to scrape through, that he wasn't killed on the spot. And - they went away anyway. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Were they fishing at the wrong time of the year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 No, they were inside the limit, inside the three mile limit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 I thought you said they were from Aberdeen?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Of course they were but that - that's where they were fishing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Were Aberdeen trawlers not allowed there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 They weren't, no
t - not inside three miles. Not inside three mile limit. They could fish anywhere outside the three mile limit right round the coast. Right round these islands. They could fish right up to the three mile limit. Right - right round the coast of Britain. No
w
 - they've got six mile limit, and twelve mile limit, at the present day. If you're going - following the common market. The Common Market they want - they don't - they - they don't want to agree with a twelve mile limit at all. They want to keep it at th
e six mile limit. And - the Scottish fishermen don't want that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 How long were you on that boat then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Now - I was on that boat from 1905. 1905 to - 1911. 1911.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 As a messroom steward all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Yes. No, no. Oh no. Oh no. I was - I was
 in the galley for a year. And then I got chief steward myself. See? And - 1911 - 1912. The winter of 1911, the winter fishing was a complete failure - round Barra. And - my father and a few more in the wintertime some of them would be going to work to th
e
 gas works in Glasgow, see. Because they couldn't afford to stop the home and do without getting some money and - my father went away, he had a boat, a fishing boat of his own. And - he went away to Glasgow and he joined a puffer, one of these puffers tha
t go around. Not - not today -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 What's a puffer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
A puffer's one of these small boats you see carrying cargo - coal, cement, sand, God knows what not, any cargo they get. Say hundred ton, two hundred ton. Tonnage see? And he joined one of them, and
 there was only three men - on deck and the skipper. And they had a bogey in the foc's'l, and it was terrible cold and they were in the Rossie dock. And - this night they came aboard after - finishing the discharging, they went ashore for a pint of beer o
r
 two pints of beer as the case may be, and they came back - and as you know there was no port holes in these puffers that you could open. There was only a skylight, a place to - a hatch, that you were going down to the foc's'l - what they call the foc's'l
, forecastle, and the three of them were sleeping there. They filled up the bogey - coal - and - closed the sk}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3034638\charrsid5125818 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 ttle on the top, went to bed. In the morning there was no signs of anybody getting up. So the skipper went up and tried the - the hatch. Well ther
e was nobody - no - he shouted down, anybody alive there now? No response. So he went down. And there were the three of them in bed - lying dead. There was my father - made signs that he was alive. But the other two were dead, were suffocated see? And - m
y
 father was taken to hospital. And in 1912 - 19 - no, 1911 it was, 1911 - he was taken to hospital and - about - December 1911, he was sent home and he was paralysed in one side - and his arm, one arm, I think it was the left - yes, the left, and the righ
t
 leg - paralysed. Then he got home in the December. And I remember going down to meet him with a pony that my grandfather had, to take him home. He was carried out - for the mailboat and he was put on the back - bareback on the pony, and ride. Went home w
ith him. Well was - he was there for six months and years - two years anyway before he could - manage to hop about.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 The family must have had a struggle to make ends meet at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Oh Lord Almighty, we had - oh only bare bare living. Bare liv
ing. And hard times for us. In fact - for all the fisherman at that winter - with that winter, it was terrible. Terrible hardship. And there was no such a thing as - what you call the - what you got today. National Assistance. No such a thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 No help at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 No, no, no, none whatever. None whatever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Not even the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
No. No. None - none at all. So - when he got a little bit that he could do a little bit with his hands there was one paymaster over there, Mr George MacDonald, and he 
went and got thread for making salmon fishing nets. See? And my father was making and getting enumeration for that, you see? Which helped him quite a lot. And the family. Eventually through time he got away and he would be going about with a stick. And wh
en he got floating around he started land leaguing, in 19 - 1906. No, 19 - no, no, 19 - 1906, 1907, 1908, 1907. No, not 1907, start land leaguing - 1906.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 So that was before he was ill then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Oh no, when he was ill - after his illness, when he got 
- when he got past his - I - I made a mistake there as regards the dates. It was in 19 - 1906 I think he got suffocated. And - start land leaguing anyway. Eventually he got to a solicitor that was in Lochmaddy, called Mr Wilson. And he got in touch with h
im. And he used to go to visit him, this Mr Wilson was paying for all his fares and - back and forth, and he started land leaguing for the island of Lewis.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 What do you mean by land leaguing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Land leaguing is to take possession. See? Land leaguers
, take possession, they took possession of this island against the - the landlord and against the - Lady Gordon Cathcart, she was the proprietor, see?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Your father was one of the first people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 The leaguer - the leader. The leader. Before we get any further here you are.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Can you tell me about how they took the island then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
Yes, that's just what it was coming too. And - they - they - they were taken to - to the Gorton goal and they were sentenced for six months. They got six months. And 
they were sent to Gorton goal. And they had the grumofoit, prison grub, they were proper criminals. See, because I visited them. And - the day that I was going in - the first - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3034638\charrsid5125818 solicitor}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818  went with me, well I asked him, I knew perfectly well that there 
would be - missing their tobacco, their smoke, and I asked the - Sir Donald Shore, is it - is it convenient for me to take in a few ounces of tobacco? Well, he says, I don't know. But, he says, we'll get it and we'll get it and we'll see, he says, what I 
c
an do with the governor, see? Will he allow it. So - we got the tobacco anyway, at the mound in Edinburgh, a shop there, a small shop there, we got it and took it to the Corton goal. My father was the first that came out. He was pleased to see us. I was l
o
oking at him, but he was - he was pretty sturdy at this all the same. He - he seemed to take the whole thing - quite cool. And - each one of them came out and when we were leaving I told my father, said, I'll be back some other time. If we could go, becau
s
e they had to get six months. So I was back and forward into Leith occasionally anyway, I would pay them a visit every time I would come in. But - he says, well, he says, I don't think, he says, that we're going to be here six months. So it was all right.
 
I wasn't - interested in - in press at the time, but seemingly - there was quite a lot of agitation from America and Canada about their sentence, in the press. And I found that out afterwards. And - at the end of six weeks - they had to release them. Or e
l
se the place would be - stormed up. Taken down. And the day they were released - there was two stations at Edinburgh then. The Waverley Station on the east side of Princes Street, east end of Princes Street, and Princes Street station on the west end. And
 
they were to be going by - from the - Waverley and such and such a time - for Oban. But - and the crowd that was there, and I was there myself, the crowd that was there was enormous - enormous. And it - there was no signs of no prisoners coming. They was 
carted some way unknown down to - to Princes Street station - and sent down to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3034638\charrsid5125818 Oban}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 . I knew nothing at all about that. At the end of six week there. So Donald Shaw, he didn't see me that day at all, he knew about it you see, but he didn't see me and I wasn'
t up in time anyway to see him, and he didn't see me at all to tell me - but - they went and I didn't see them at all. They came to Oban anyway and there was a tremendous welcome there waiting them. Pipers and all the rest of it. And still more when they 
arrived in Castlebay.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Pipers again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
Pipers again. Yes. Flags. The - the kind that - that was there at the time I don't know. Some - some pieces of blanket supposedly, something like that. Or old bags, white bags - flour bags. All - were - oh trem
endous number. So they got to their own homes then. How - when they - when they - when they were sitting at the court, the Judge told them, now are you going back to where you came from now? My father said, yes. We're going there and we're going to take p
ossession of the island. Previous to that you see they had some - some of them put some - cattle over here, before they went away. A cow or two or three, see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Did they bring them over at night time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Well - well I don't know about that now, but t
hey were put over anyway. It's quite - it's quite possible it was done at night in - in the dark. But it was done anyway, see. And - in fact they was tilling potatoes - too in broad daylight, they didn't see, took possession of the land, and the wheat - a
nd - planted for - for the season, potatoes. Well - after that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 So they brought the cattle over and tilled the potatoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
Yes. And - that was in 1908. 1909 they were in full possession. We had - the house that we had over in Castlebay, it was a w
ooden shed, same as a - a squatter, as a cot - cotters, they called them squatters. Then that had no land at all, no - no croft. And my father was one of them, and all these that's there. No crofts at all. Just - that house was only about ten yards from h
i
gh water mark than that. Probably about five. There was two other next to our house - just about five yards from high water mark. So - in 1909 they were in full swing over here. And it was - our house was over here at 19 - 1909. Up here in the square. Whe
re - up near the Post Office.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Did they build the houses themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
Yes. It's only a wooden house that we had, every one of them had only - only wooden houses. They had - just disconnect them over the other side and - carry them over. Set them up again. What do you call that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Did you have any animals over in Barra before you came?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 No. No, no, no. No. Nothing at all, not even a hen. Not even a hen, no.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
Then you came to near the Post Office, how many animals did you have afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
We had no animals at all when we came here. Of course I wasn't at home at all you know. I was away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 When did you come back then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
I didn't come back 'til 1912. 1912, my father was on his deathbed then. But - 1912 - previous to that - I left
 the - the Minnerhouse, in the Minner after the Brenda, I was there chief steward, and - I don't know what came - came round at all. She was going out anyway, she was going out to the Mediterranean and I didn't go with her at all. I left her. I was - I ca
me home in 19 - no, I went to - to Glasgow. And I got a job in Singers' in Clydebank.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 What did you do there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 I was a foundry clerk there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 A clerk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
Yes. Foundry clerk in Singers' in 1911. I was stopping out in Addisland. Where - lodgin
g with a woman which was my own cousin's wife at the time. And - my father got badly then. And he was badly for - for - going on for a year. But my mother told me she is not - because were - poor circumstances you know and they're only depending on the li
ttle that I was doing. Every penny that I was earning I was sending home. Never even kept a - a ha'penny for myself sometimes. Yes. Sending it home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 So you were the chief breadwinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 I was the chief breadwinner, I was the oldest of the family. A
nd - when - at last - they sent for me. When I told Mr Govern, he was the head clerk - and Singers' was at that time - I told them that I couldn't stay on. Well, he says - I'll keep your job open, he says, for a month. At the end of the month, he says, wr
i
te me if you can't come. So - at the end of the month I wrote to him and I told him we couldn't manage - manage. And in July 1912 my father - on the fourth of July he died up here. See. Well after that - I couldn't leave now, seeing that they were going t
o
 take possession of some crofts, the crofts was where - where - were located out to each - each tenant, see, and I had mine, my father's at number six, see and I had to stop at home and start cultivating it. See? And try - fishing as a sideline. So - I st
arted at that and I kept going and I got this house built.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 You built this house yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
Yes, by - well I got a mason. I - I didn't do the mason work at all. No. But I - I - I - no, I got a mason for to do it. And when it was - finished I got a 
joiner, a close friend of my own and - he - fixed it up. When the - 1912 - 1913 - I kept going, '14 I kept going. But - '14 came, I had to get out. Either go to sea or go to the Army. One of the two. In first world war. So I decided, I'll go to sea. And I
 
went as a merchant seaman then. Yes. As an able seaman then. And I kept on right through the - throughout the war - the war, 'til 1919 I got released. Demolised, 1919. And in 19 - November 1917 I was torpedoed - five hundred miles west of Gibraltar. And b
y
 God, I can assure you, that it wasn't a - a - a - a pleasant thing, at eight o'clock in the morning we got torpedoed. And three of our - three of our - our - firemen, they was - well of course you were stuck just above the poop, you know, at the - do you
 
know anything about the ships yourselves? Four hatches, well the - the after hatch, number four hatch, the torpedo struck her just at the - after end of - of number four hatch. And the coolies - Arabs they were, Arabay, Arab firemen - they were on the sta
rboard side, just where the - where the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3034638\charrsid5125818 torpedo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
 struck her. And do you know that - they were thrown - three of them were thrown right through the - the roof of the - of the - the deckhouse. Yes, they were in bed at the time. See? They were scattered all ove
r. However, we got into the boats, and picked up the - after eight hours in the - in the lifeboat, by an American cruiser, at the time. And - taken to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3034638\charrsid5125818 Gibraltar}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
Did you settle here again after the war then, you settled down on the croft again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
Oh yes. Yes. I came home after the - 1919, I came home and - started the croft, kept the croft going. Got cattle, sheep over in Sandray, sheep over there and - lobster fishing. And herring fishing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 You've done that too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Yes. I was at that and all. Now - in 1931 - 1931 - I got - no, I got married.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 You got married in 1931?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Is your wife from Barra too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
Aye. From Mingulay previous. Yes. Mingulay. Her father came from Mingulay. And her mother came from - Tangusdale, down th
e west side. And - I settled down then. And I started lobster fishing again with my father-in-law. We got a small boat - I had a small boat of my own anyway since 19 - 1908 I bought it in Castlebay, I got my father to buy it. Yes, at the time, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Did you work on it at that time though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
No, I didn't but my father was using it, yes. Anybody that wanted to. At that time there was no such a thing as ferries or nothing of that - that - at that time. We used to do all the ferrying, the lobster fisher
men. Yes, didn't matter who came to the boat you were getting - passengers, doesn't matter who he was. And no asking - no asking for - for fares or nothing else. No, no. No such a thing. But not today. I have to pay dear today for to go across to Castleba
y myself. By heavens, you're telling me. Whoever - however - now where were we now -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 You were saying how you came back here and got the sheep and cattle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
Oh yes, yes. Oh - now, were two seasons, two years working with an Oban small boat. Sixteen 
- sixteen and a half feet and keel, and we used to go in the winter time in the months of October when the weather was getting boisterous round these islands. We used to go to Barra Head. Five of us. And take the small boat with us. Haul her up in - at ni
ght time on the slip in Bereray in Barra Head, and putting it out in morning again. Keep it clean - working cleaners there for a month. And the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid3034638\charrsid5125818 lighthouse man}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818  Norman Castle that was attending to Barra Head at that time, it was a loch station. But he used to
 go out with this - the - mails, McAuley, he's over there and he's got his son over there yet. The old man is dead. He used to take up the - the lobsters to Catlebay that we were catching in the month of October and were making a good thing of it, at the 
t
ime. More so than in summertime. Because - in the summertime when we were - was trading with Billingsgate, that's the only market; that we could get for lobsters at that time. See, by the time they would get to Billingsgate we were getting what they call 
a blue form, that they was - not fit for human consumption, see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
You were telling me about starting the croft, can you tell me what you grew on the croft?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
Oh - potatoes. Barley, oats, that was all. That was growing on the croft - on the crofts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 You didn't have any other vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
No. No, no. No but that. No, no. No such a thing round here as vegetables. Not with the - not with the crofters. Not with the crofters. We - we weren't so far advanced at that - at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 You had sheep and cattle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 So you had milk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Milk, plenty of it. Plenty of milk. Plenty of milk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 How did you manage for meat, did you eat your own mutton?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Well - always - at the Whitsuntide, right on from there we used to keep our
 own - what they call wethers. Wethers. They were two year old or three year old that was grazing on - on Dandray. We used to kill one every - now and then. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Did you have any meat in the winter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Oh very seldom, very seldom. Very seldom. Very seldom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Fish?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
Plenty of fish. Oh plenty of fish. And in my time in Castlebay - fish was the - staple diet. Yes, in Castlebay. Oh yes. Yes, yes. Because you would - you could pick up any kind of fish in - at Catlebay. Any kind at all, that was
 left - on the beach there for anybody to take - to take it home. It was that plentiful round here at that time. And there was - fish that you can't get - that you can't buy today, was strewn on the shore in Castlebay there - not - nobody go near it. And 
that was turbot. Turbot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 People wouldn't pick it up and use it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
They wouldn't bother with it, they had plenty of other - plenty of other fish. Today - you can't buy it in the shop. Yes, that's - that's - well that's fact. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Was there a township here that organised the grazing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 You mean - a committee. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Were you on the committee?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Yes, I was few years in that and all. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 What kind of things did you decide?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Well - you had to decide as regards rams - from 
the Department of Agriculture, bulls, whatever bull you wanted - all you to do was in - fill in a form, send it in to the department and if - if they sanction it, well there you are, you are given the bull free. You had to keep it yourself during the time
 you had it. See? The same thing with the lamb - with the rams. You were getting it from the Department.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Was there common grazing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
Common? Oh yes. Oh yes. In fact you can see the - the arable ground, it's fenced in. Its fenced on you see on both 
sides. What they call the first - the first name that they latterly got was Lowerton, that's in that section. And Upperton, this is this section, so that's my section, Upperton. That's the way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 And you were each allowed so many sheep on the common ground?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 There was no sheep allowed in the \{BLANK\}
 at all, none at all on the - of course on the cool side there. See? There's a boundary fence there as you come through the gate, well - on - from this side there was no - no sheep allowed at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
I don't - I don't know, that was department - it was - what you call that now?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Because of the sand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
No, no. No, no. It was on account of - och, I can't remember now the name of the - it was - the sheep club. It was a club. Tha
t the Vatersay and Aristow, there's twenty - twenty tenants - tenants in Vatersay and eight in Aristow, that's away down at the back of the brae there. See? But there's nobody there now, not a soul. And - sheep club it was. And you had a share of - about 
fifteen to twenty sheep, each tenant. And that was grazing on - on - Sandray. And there was no sheep allowed here at all. And there was no dogs allowed here. Only one dog - by the shepherd, that was looking after Sandray.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Did he live on Sandray?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
No. Only when - lambing time. Lambing time. I was one - one season there and all. At lambing. Aye. Aye. There was the four of us there. Yes, the lambing season.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 A lonely time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Oh lonely, oh yes, yes. But I enjoyed it all the same. Yes. You had t
o be there over for six weeks. Yes, lambing time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Did you plough the land or did you make lazy beds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
Lazy beds. When this was ploughed. Yes. Vatersay was. But - over - in - in Aristow it was lazy beds, that they - that they - had. Of course we h
ad - four horses, club horses. Everything was club as regards - the agricultural - it was a club stock - see - and - we had four horses, four carts, two ploughs and - what do you call them - that you go after your ploughing is finished - harrows - harrows
, that's right, that's right, that's right. That's right. Yes. Well, there you are.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Could you tell me where your father came from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Yes. Yes. My father was born in Nairn. In Nairn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 How did he come here then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Oh well he came here when my
 grandfather came here to the - he was the first - the first fisherman that took a herring net to Barra - to Castlebay, my grandfather. Anthony Campbell.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 So your father came here when he was young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 When he was - when he was sixteen - he was - be
fore he left Nairn he was going in for coopering trade. Yes. Before he left Nairn.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 He gave that up and went on the fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
That's right. That's right, when he came over here when his - when his father came here. The family came over - came to - to Barra.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Did the family have a croft?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 No, no. No, no. Just to themself, the grandfather.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 You told me about the squatters hut he had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 The only jobs he had, you mentioned the fishing and the gas works?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8731373 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 Were there any other jobs that he did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8202071 DC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9518286\charrsid5125818 
No, nothing - while he was at the - at the - coopering trade, that was all that I know. And fishing. He kept on the fishing all the time, when he came to Barra.
